<exercise checkit-seed="0006" checkit-slug="L5" checkit-title="Argument Analysis via Form">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Use a common form of argument to decide if the following argument is valid. Cite the argument form you are matching by name, and state how you are assigning the variables P, Q, and possibly R in order to line up with that form.
        </p>
        <p>if it is false that there is no traffic today, then I exercise regularly. there is no traffic today. Therefore, it is false that I exercise regularly.</p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p> The argument structure is <me>\text{Premise 1: } \sim P \rightarrow Q</me> <me>\text{Premise 2: } P</me> <me>\text{Conclusion: } \sim Q</me> This is not valid by the fallacy of the inverse.</p>
    </answer>
</exercise>
